In the peer-to-peer model, there is no server that co-ordinates the network services; each
device is both a client and a server, and communicates with all other peers. The provision of
network services is distributed across the devices.
The challenge with peer-to-peer is co-ordination, since there is no obvious “authoritative”
source to query where to find certain services.
There is no single point of failure or risk.
There is no need to spend money on expensive hardware or software, as the
load is shared among all the clients themselves.
As the size of the network grows, so too does the scale of services it can
provide. Each additional peer also adds additional capacity.
Services can be provided directly from one computer to another,
Maintaining settings, security patches and synchronization of data across
multiple nodes on the network can be very challenging.
